# Environment Variables

## Never use `process.env` directly

Import the type-safe env object from **`@hermes/env`** (Hermes apps and packages) or **`@mediapulse/env`** (Mediapulse apps, agents, and packages). Use subpath exports where defined (e.g. `@hermes/env/hermes-worker`, `@mediapulse/env/agents-delivery`).

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const dbUrl = process.env.ORCHESTRATION_DATABASE_URL;

// ✅ GOOD (Hermes)
import { env } from "@hermes/env";
const dbUrl = env.ORCHESTRATION_DATABASE_URL;

// ✅ GOOD (Mediapulse)
import { env } from "@mediapulse/env";
```

## Sensitive values must NOT have the `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix

Database passwords, API keys, tokens, and any credential used to access backend resources must be server-only (no `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix). `NEXT_PUBLIC_` values are inlined into the client bundle and visible to anyone inspecting the page source.

## Document every variable in `env.example`

When adding or changing an environment variable:

1. Add it to the correct package’s `env.example` (or per-app / per-agent example file) with a descriptive comment.
2. Include `env-to-t3` annotations: `#required`, `#number`, `#default`, etc.
3. Rebuild the env package: `pnpm build` in `packages/hermes/env` and/or `packages/mediapulse/env`.

```dotenv
# The URL of the Postgres database pool
ORCHESTRATION_DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres:root@localhost:5432/postgres?schema=orchestration" #required
```

## Static vs dynamic awareness

- `NEXT_PUBLIC_` values and values read in static RSCs are baked in at **build time**. Changing them after build has no effect.
- Values read in dynamic RSCs take effect at **runtime** (after server restart).
